The paper discusses the restricted isometry property (RIP) which is a concept in compressed sensing and statistical learning, falling under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the problem of detecting dense subgraphs, which is a topic in graph theory and algorithms, falling under the categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses the computational complexity of certifying RIP, which involves solving optimization problems, falling under the category of numerical analysis (cs.NA).
